rban men operate in a system of cultural economy where reputation is essential for financial success. That reputation is measured by familiarity with and access to the fashionable and expensive, which leads to a paradoxical state of affairs in which the wasting of wealth is essential to its accumulation. Using the consumption of Western goods to express their cultural mastery over Western taste, Newell argues, bluffeurs engage a global hierarchy that is profoundly modern, one that values performance over authenticity­—highlighting the counterfeit nature of modernity itself.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aSocial status -- Côte d'Ivoire. 0aSocial statuszCôte d'Ivoire. 0aUrban youth -- Côte d'Ivoire -- Economic conditions -- 21st century. 0aUrban youth -- Côte d'Ivoire -- Social conditions -- 21st century. 0aUrban youthzCôte d'IvoirexEconomic conditionsy21st century. 0aUrban youthzCôte d'IvoirexSocial conditionsy21st century. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z97831106353860 cprintz978022657519340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226575216423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226575216/original  a978-3-11-063538-6  University of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles